  "id": "019d417d-c7b5-7d90-8453-c26850e4e030",
  "content": "# Multi-Channel RAG: Per-Type HNSW Indexes -- Implementation Record (2026-03-31)\n\n## What\nImplemented per-memory-type HNSW indexes in LiteStore and a MultiChannelSearcher for the composable pipeline (issue #13).\n\n## Key Implementation Decisions\n\n1. **Single global HNSW ID counter** instead of per-type counters with prefixed keys. The original spec (D2) called for prefixed string keys in HNSW_TO_UUID/UUID_TO_HNSW, but these tables use u64 keys. A single AtomicU64 counter produces globally unique IDs across all 5 per-type indexes, so existing Redb tables work unchanged with no schema migration.\n\n2. **Single ArcSwap wrapping entire HnswMap** instead of per-type ArcSwap. All 5 indexes swap atomically via one ArcSwap::store() call during blue-green rebuild. This eliminates the torn-read window where a search could see a mix of old and new indexes.\n\n3. **Empty HNSW indexes skipped during flush.** hnsw_rs file_dump fails on empty graphs. On reload, missing per-type files get fresh empty indexes. This handles the common case where most entries cluster in 1-2 memory types.\n\n4. **MAX_ELEMENTS_PER_TYPE = 20,000** (100K total across 5 types). Reduces memory footprint vs 5x100K. Skewed workloads may hit the cap on dominant types.\n\n5. **Graph expansion handled by pipeline Expander stage**, not per-channel in MultiChannelSearcher. This preserves the pipeline's single-responsibility design.\n\n## Review Insights Worth Remembering\n- hnsw_rs get_nb_point() can be used to check if an index has entries before searching or flushing\n- BM25 channel needs 3x over-fetch to compensate for post-filter by memory_type (no native per-type FTS method exists)\n- Union search lookup_limit should be 3x (not 2x) to survive scope post-filtering across types\n- MemoryType derives Hash + Eq, so it works as HashMap key\n\n## What Blocked\n- hnsw_rs file_dump fails silently on empty indexes (returns error, not panic). Required get_nb_point() guard.\n- The linter/hooks switched the working branch back to master mid-session, requiring a branch re-checkout.",
